# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ktor-server
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:ktor-server/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:ktor-server/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:ktor-server/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] One of Kotlin's stated goals is to compile as quickly as Java.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] In February 2012, JetBrains open-sourced the project under the Apache 2 license.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains expected Kotlin to drive sales of IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.0 was released on 15 February 2016, which is considered the first officially stable release, and JetBrains has committed to long-term backwards compatibility starting with this version.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] At Google I/O 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced that Kotlin is now its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Development lead Andrey Breslav has said that Kotlin is designed to be an industrial-strength object-oriented language, a "better language" than Java, and still fully interoperable with Java code, allowing companies to make a gradual migration from Java to Kotlin.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] For example, `@file:JvmName("JavaClassName")`.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin provides the following keywords to restrict visibility for top-level declarations (such as classes) and for class members: `public`, `internal`, `protected`, and `private`.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin distinguishes between nullable and non-nullable data types.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] All nullable objects must be declared with a "?" postfix after the type name.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin supports higher-order functions and anonymous functions, or **lambdas**.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] If a lambda takes parameters, they are declared within the braces and followed by the -> operator.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin Multiplatform enables a single codebase to target multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, the web, Android, and iOS.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Compose Multiplatform is a multiplatform UI framework based on Jetpack Compose.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] It is Jetpack Compose for Android ported to Windows, macOS, Linux, web, and iOS.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] For example, the Text composable function displays a text label on the screen.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] In 2018, Kotlin was the fastest-growing language on GitHub, with 2.6 times as many developers as in 2017.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] It is the fourth-most-loved programming language according to the 2020 Stack Overflow Developer Survey.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin was also awarded the O'Reilly Open Source Software Conference Breakout Award for 2019.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] A large number of companies in various industries use Kotlin, including Google, Amazon Web Services, Netflix and McDonald's.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] When Kotlin was announced as an official Android development language at Google I/O in May 2017, it became the third language fully supported for Android, after Java and C++.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] As of 2020, Kotlin was the most widely used language on Android, with Google estimating that 70% of the top 1,000 apps on the Play Store were written in Kotlin.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Google itself had 60 apps written in Kotlin, including Maps and Drive.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Many Android apps, such as Google Home, were in the process of migrating to Kotlin and therefore use both Kotlin and Java.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin on Android is seen as beneficial for its null-safety and features that make code shorter and more readable.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Ktor is a JetBrains Kotlin-first framework for building server and client applications.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] The Spring Framework officially added Kotlin support with version 5, on 4 January 2017.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] To further support Kotlin, Spring has translated all its documentation into Kotlin and added built-in support for many Kotlin-specific features, such as coroutines.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] In 2020, JetBrains found in a survey of developers who use Kotlin that 56% used it for mobile apps, while 47% used it for a web backend.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Just over a third of all Kotlin developers said they were migrating from another language.
[src:ktor-server/kotlin-programming-language] Most Kotlin users targeted Android (or the JVM), with only 6% using Kotlin Native.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains offers a variety of integrated development environments (IDEs), such as IntelliJ IDEA, PyCharm, Rider, WebStorm and CLion.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It also created the Kotlin programming language in 2011, which can run in a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains, initially called IntelliJ Software, was founded in 2000 in Prague by three Russian software developers: Sergey Dmitriev, Valentin Kipyatkov and Eugene Belyaev.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company's first product was IntelliJ Renamer, a tool for code refactoring in Java.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2012 CEO Sergey Dmitriev was replaced by Oleg Stepanov and Maxim Shafirov.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2021 *The New York Times* stated that unknown parties might have embedded malware in JetBrains' TeamCity CI/CD software that led to the SolarWinds hack and other widespread security compromises.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In a press release, JetBrains said they had not been contacted by any government or security agency and had not "taken part or been involved in this attack in any way".
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The CEO of one of the affected companies, SolarWinds, "asked about the possibility that software tools made by JetBrains, which speeds the development and testing of code, was the pathway".
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the company suspended sales and R&D activities in Russia indefinitely, as well as sales in Belarus.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains' Russian legal entity was liquidated on 21 February 2023.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In September 2023, JetBrains acquired the company Code Buddy and its two main products, JPA Buddy and React Buddy.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The tools were integrated into IntelliJ IDEA Ultimate and the team joined JetBrains to continue their development.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Effective 1 February 2024, Kirill Skrygan replaced Maxim Shafirov as CEO.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In December 2025, JetBrains unified IntelliJ IDEA into a single distribution, merging the previously separate Community Edition and Ultimate Edition.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Under the new model, all Ultimate features require a subscription to unlock, while the IDE remains fully functional and free for both commercial and non-commercial projects without a subscription, including more features than the Community Edition previously offered.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains has achieved significant financial growth without external funding.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company reported 5.6% revenue growth in 2023, following 11% growth in 2022.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains is profitable with $200 million in EBITDA generated in 2020.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company has never raised external capital.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The following is a non-exhaustive list of integrated development environments (IDEs) distributed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The JetBrains Marketplace offers 8,860 plugins that extend the functionality of JetBrains IDEs.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] ReSharper is a Visual Studio extension for .NET developers, first released in 2004.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It is JetBrains' longest-standing commercial product and, according to JetBrains, has accumulated over 2.5 million downloads, making it the most popular extension on the Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It was also a key revenue source for JetBrains in its early years.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] ReSharper provides on-the-fly code quality analysis for C#, VB.NET, XAML, ASP.NET, JavaScript, TypeScript, CSS, HTML, and XML.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Its features include code refactoring, code completion, navigation, find usages, and code formatting.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The extension offers more than 2,200 on-the-fly code inspections and over 60 refactorings and 450 context actions.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Starting with version 2026.1, ReSharper expanded beyond Visual Studio to support Visual Studio Code and compatible editors such as Cursor, bringing JetBrains' C# tooling to a broader range of development environments.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The VS Code extension provides real-time code analysis, refactorings, and navigation for C#, XAML, Razor, and Blazor, and includes a Solution Explorer as well as built-in unit testing support for NUnit, xUnit.net, and MSTest.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] ReSharper's development influenced the creation of JetBrains' standalone .NET IDE, Rider; although plans for a dedicated ReSharper IDE were explored and later abandoned after the release of Visual Studio 2005, the work done on ReSharper ultimately formed the foundation for Rider.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] ReSharper is available as a standalone license or as part of the dotUltimate subscription, which also includes Rider, dotTrace, dotCover, and dotMemory.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Kotlin is an open-source, statically typed programming language that runs on the Java Virtual Machine and also compiles to JavaScript or native code (via LLVM).
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The name comes from the Kotlin Island, near St.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In May 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android, and at Google I/O 2019, Google declared Kotlin its preferred language for Android app development.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains MPS is an open-source language workbench for domain-specific languages.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Ktor is a Kotlin-based programming framework for developing "connected applications", using the same framework on both server (JVM) and client (JavaScript, Android, and iOS).
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Kotlin Multiplatform (KMP) is a JetBrains technology that allows developers to share Kotlin code across multiple platforms, including Android, iOS, desktop, web, and server.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It reached stable status with the release of Kotlin 1.9.20 in November 2023.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The related Compose Multiplatform framework, which enables shared user interfaces, became stable for iOS in 2025.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] TeamCity is a continuous integration and continuous delivery server developed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It is a server-based web application written in Java.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] *The New York Times* reported that TeamCity may have been used by Russian hackers of US governmental and private agencies, in potentially "the biggest breach of United States networks in history".
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Upsource was a code review and repository browsing tool supporting Git, GitHub, Mercurial, Perforce and/or Subversion repositories from a central location.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains released a new developer collaboration tool, Space, in 2019.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It began sunsetting Upsource in 2022, officially ending support for the product in January 2023.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In May 2024, JetBrains rebranded Space to SpaceCode to focus on Git hosting and code reviews.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] YouTrack is a proprietary, commercial web-based bug tracker, issue tracking system, and project management software developed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Qodana is a code quality analysis tool that uses static code analysis to help users with code reviews, building quality gates, and the implementation of code quality guidelines.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It was publicly launched in July 2023 and can be used with IDEs in JetBrains's ecosystem, has CI/CD pipeline integration, while supporting code analysis in over 60 programming languages.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains AI Assistant is offered in most JetBrains IDEs as a set of AI-assisted software development tools.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The assistant uses models from OpenAI and Google, as well as proprietary models developed by JetBrains, such as the Mellum model released in April 2025.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Junie is an AI coding agent developed by JetBrains, launched in January 2025 in closed preview.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Unlike the AI Assistant, which focuses on code completion, Junie is designed to function as an AI agent for coding.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In April 2025, JetBrains made Junie generally available.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Datalore is a web application for data analysis and visualization, which is focused specifically on the machine learning environment in Python.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains Academy is an online platform to learn programming, including such programming languages as Python, Java, and Kotlin.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The Academy was introduced by JetBrains in 2019, and reached 200,000 users by July 2020.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Certifications were added in November 2021 after community feedback prioritized verifiability of the work done on projects.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains has also developed the EduTools plugin for students, which is compatible with IntelliJ IDEA (Ultimate, Community, Educational), Android Studio, CLion, GoLand, PhpStorm, PyCharm (Professional, Community, Educational), WebStorm.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2009, JetBrains open-sourced the core functionality of IntelliJ IDEA by offering the free Community Edition.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] It is built on the IntelliJ Platform and includes its sources.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains released both under Apache License 2.0.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2010, Android support became a part of the Community Edition, and two years later Google announced its Android Studio, the IDE for mobile development on Android platform built on the Community Edition of IntelliJ IDEA and an official alternative to Eclipse Android Developer Tool.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] After two years of development JetBrains open-sourced Kotlin in February 2012.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In June 2015, it was announced that the support of Eclipse ADT would be discontinued, making Android Studio the official tool for Android App development.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In January 2020, JetBrains released a geometric monospaced font called JetBrains Mono, made the default font for its IDEs, under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The font is designed for reading source code by being optimized for reading vertically with support for programming ligatures.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] As a private company, JetBrains does not disclose detailed financial statements.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] However, its annual highlight reports indicate consistent growth.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In its 2023 highlights, the company reported a 5.6% year-over-year revenue growth and noted 11.4 million recurring active users.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] This followed an 11% revenue growth in 2022, when the company reported having 15.9 million users.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company's business model is primarily based on software subscriptions.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In recent years, JetBrains has adjusted its model in response to market trends.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] This includes making more of its IDEs available with free, non-commercial licenses, such as for RustRover, and unifying its flagship IDE, IntelliJ IDEA, to offer a single download with both free and paid features.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains maintains partnerships with more than 140 resellers and numerous technology partners worldwide.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] According to partnership data, JetBrains has 49 partners, including 41 technology partners and 8 channel partners, with Salesforce as its largest partner.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains has an active technology partnership with Google Cloud.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2022, the companies partnered to deliver integration between Google Cloud Workstations and JetBrains remote development, allowing developers to use JetBrains IDEs with Google Cloud's managed development environments.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] This integration gave Cloud Workstations support for popular JetBrains IDEs such as IntelliJ IDEA, PyCharm, and Rider, allowing developers to take advantage of managed and customizable environments in Google Cloud within their preferred IDE.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2024, JetBrains extended its collaboration with Google Cloud to integrate Google's Gemini models into JetBrains AI Assistant, making it the first tool of its kind to combine functionality from OpenAI's GPT-4o, Gemini, and JetBrains' proprietary models.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The collaboration leveraged Google Cloud's Vertex AI to expand the pool of large language models (LLMs) available to AI Assistant users, with Gemini Pro 1.5 and Flash 1.5 adding a long context window, advanced reasoning, and high-volume, low-latency capabilities.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] With JetBrains AI Enterprise, organisations were given the ability to configure which LLM their teams use, while for other users the assistant automatically selects the most suitable model for each task.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Later that year, starting from version 2024.3 of JetBrains AI Assistant, users were able to select their preferred LLM directly within the AI chat interface.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The partnership further expanded in 2025, when JetBrains integrated Gemini 3 Pro into both its AI Assistant and its AI coding agent Junie, with JetBrains noting that the new model showed more than a 50% improvement over Gemini 2.5 Pro in solved benchmark tasks.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Google Cloud also made Gemini Code Assist available as a plugin for JetBrains IDEs, supporting real-time code completions, full-function generation, and natural-language-to-code conversion within the JetBrains ecosystem.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains participates in various strategic collaborations, including the Java Community Process Executive Committee, Kotlin Foundation, and supports JUnit 5.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company also partners with Unity for RiderFlow and GitLab to optimize review experiences.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains provides extensive support to educational institutions and the developer community.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] In 2024, 1,840,580 students and 94,041 teachers benefited from complimentary JetBrains educational packs, while 954,277 students received special discounts for license renewal upon graduation.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Additionally, 2,172 schools and universities received 190,459 educational subscriptions for classroom assistance, and 26,100 students from 596 training courses and boot camps received free subscriptions.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The company supports the open source community with 5,952 projects receiving 11,364 complimentary licenses.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Through the User Group Support Program, 611 tech communities from 89 countries and regions obtained 3,916 licenses.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The Developer Recognition Program honored 1,284 community experts with complimentary All Products Pack subscriptions.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] Additionally, 12,615 customers benefited from the Startup discount, and JetBrains sponsored 155 IT events.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] JetBrains conducts annual Developer Ecosystem surveys to understand industry trends.
[src:ktor-server/ktor] The 2024 survey was based on input from 23,262 developers and provides insights into programming language usage, development practices, and industry trends.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:ktor-server/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
